1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,420
Now we will talk about how we can affect tax generation results using

2

00:00:04,420  -->  00:00:10,800
various generation parameters that are available in Hugging Face and other libraries.

3

00:00:10,800  -->  00:00:13,280
To avoid some possible confusion,

4

00:00:13,280  -->  00:00:15,905
there are two types of parameters.

5

00:00:15,905  -->  00:00:22,570
Model parameters; these are parameters that were set during a model training,

6

00:00:22,570  -->  00:00:25,345
and generation parameters;

7

00:00:25,345  -->  00:00:32,415
these can affect the result of a tax generation when we use a model after it was trained.

8

00:00:32,415  -->  00:00:35,490
We have already seen one parameter,

9

00:00:35,490  -->  00:00:38,110
which is the maximum number of tokens,

10

00:00:38,110  -->  00:00:40,690
tax generation process should return.

11

00:00:40,690  -->  00:00:44,830
In Hugging Face, it is called max length parameter.

12

00:00:44,830  -->  00:00:48,870
As you can imagine, the higher this parameter is,

13

00:00:48,870  -->  00:00:53,870
the longer the output the tax generation process will produce.

14

00:00:53,950  -->  00:00:56,190
One [inaudible], however,

15

00:00:56,190  -->  00:01:00,010
is that it defines a maximum number of tokens and

16

00:01:00,010  -->  00:01:05,810
tax generation can return an output that is shorter than this value.

17

00:01:05,810  -->  00:01:08,670
During the tax generation process,

18

00:01:08,670  -->  00:01:13,030
a model can emit a special end of sequence token that will

19

00:01:13,030  -->  00:01:18,250
stop the generation process even before it reached the specified limit.

20

00:01:18,250  -->  00:01:23,070
Now, let's talk about how we can generate text using an LLM.

21

00:01:23,070  -->  00:01:26,990
One simple option is that every time we want to generate

22

00:01:26,990  -->  00:01:32,760
a new token is to select a token with the highest probability.

23

00:01:33,260  -->  00:01:38,600
Once our model produces the probabilities from the softmax layer,

24

00:01:38,600  -->  00:01:43,360
it might be logical to just pick the word with the highest probability.

25

00:01:43,360  -->  00:01:45,220
Once we select a token,

26

00:01:45,220  -->  00:01:49,800
we can add it to the input and then generate the new token,

27

00:01:49,800  -->  00:01:54,040
and then repeat this process again and again.

28

00:01:54,040  -->  00:01:57,720
This approach, when we always pick a token with

29

00:01:57,720  -->  00:02:01,845
the highest probability is also called greedy decoding,

30

00:02:01,845  -->  00:02:06,820
because we are always greedily pick a token with the highest probability.

31

00:02:06,820  -->  00:02:09,620
There is, however an issue with this approach.

32

00:02:09,620  -->  00:02:12,920
If we pick a token with the highest probability,

33

00:02:12,920  -->  00:02:17,180
it can lead to boring and repetitive results.

34

00:02:17,180  -->  00:02:21,080
One surprising fix for this is to add a little bit of

35

00:02:21,080  -->  00:02:27,440
randomness and pick less probable tokens when generating output.

36

00:02:27,440  -->  00:02:32,500
We also have control over how much randomness we want to add.

37

00:02:32,500  -->  00:02:35,760
We will look into this later and you will be able

38

00:02:35,760  -->  00:02:39,940
to experiment with this in the upcoming exercise.

39

00:02:39,940  -->  00:02:44,520
Picking a random token is called multinomial sampling.

40

00:02:44,520  -->  00:02:51,120
If you recall, we can use the output as a softmax layer as a probability distribution.

41

00:02:51,120  -->  00:02:55,040
We can pick a token randomly using this distribution,

42

00:02:55,040  -->  00:02:57,880
and the higher the probability of a token,

43

00:02:57,880  -->  00:03:01,630
the higher the chance that it will be selected.

44

00:03:01,630  -->  00:03:07,560
In this case, if an LLM has returned to tokens with this distribution,

45

00:03:07,560  -->  00:03:11,080
we'll pick powerful in roughly 10% of cases,

46

00:03:11,080  -->  00:03:15,540
trained in roughly 9% of cases, and so on.

47

00:03:15,540  -->  00:03:17,880
Once we've picked a token,

48

00:03:17,880  -->  00:03:20,760
we can repeat the process as before and

49

00:03:20,760  -->  00:03:24,420
add it to the input and then generate the next token.

50

00:03:24,420  -->  00:03:27,620
This new input will give us a new distribution,

51

00:03:27,620  -->  00:03:31,775
and then we can pick the next token randomly, and so on.

52

00:03:31,775  -->  00:03:37,470
There is however an issue with only looking at one next token at a time.

53

00:03:37,470  -->  00:03:43,290
It can lead to suboptimal results when selecting the follow up tokens.

54

00:03:43,290  -->  00:03:47,390
It could be that if we selected a lower probability token.

55

00:03:47,390  -->  00:03:51,170
First, it could lead to better result sequences.

56

00:03:51,170  -->  00:03:55,470
A way to fix it is that instead of generating only a single sequence,

57

00:03:55,470  -->  00:04:00,045
is to try to generate multiple sequences at the same time,

58

00:04:00,045  -->  00:04:03,480
and then select the best result at the end.

59

00:04:03,480  -->  00:04:06,900
We can't try all possible token combinations

60

00:04:06,900  -->  00:04:10,680
on every step since it will quickly become unmanageable.

61

00:04:10,680  -->  00:04:13,220
To evaluate multiple sequences,

62

00:04:13,220  -->  00:04:16,500
we can use the algorithm called beam search.

63

00:04:16,500  -->  00:04:19,160
Instead of generating a single output,

64

00:04:19,160  -->  00:04:24,020
it tries to generate several sequences using a few different tokens.

65

00:04:24,020  -->  00:04:26,120
At every step of the algorithm,

66

00:04:26,120  -->  00:04:30,180
we keep and best sequences so far and we'll try to

67

00:04:30,180  -->  00:04:34,780
generate new sequences starting from the sequences we have.

68

00:04:34,780  -->  00:04:38,520
Then we just repeat this process multiple times.

69

00:04:38,520  -->  00:04:41,740
Here is an example of how this works.

70

00:04:41,740  -->  00:04:46,800
Instead of generating just one sequence from the initial prompt,

71

00:04:46,800  -->  00:04:52,780
we try to generate two sequences using two most probable next tokens,

72

00:04:52,780  -->  00:04:56,640
which are powerful and trained in this case.

73

00:04:56,640  -->  00:05:00,840
This process produces two more sequences that we again

74

00:05:00,840  -->  00:05:05,550
pass to our model to get two new probability distributions.

75

00:05:05,550  -->  00:05:09,255
In this case, we have n = 2,

76

00:05:09,255  -->  00:05:14,790
which means that we have two sequences we consider on each step.

77

00:05:14,790  -->  00:05:17,440
Having two sequences, we can pick

78

00:05:17,440  -->  00:05:21,680
two more tokens that will result in most likely outputs,

79

00:05:21,680  -->  00:05:26,220
and we will have two more sequences that we can use for the next step.

80

00:05:26,220  -->  00:05:29,160
When we are randomly selecting the next token given

81

00:05:29,160  -->  00:05:33,550
the probability distribution returned by the softmax function.

82

00:05:33,550  -->  00:05:39,580
We also have control over what tokens to pick when selecting the next word.

83

00:05:39,580  -->  00:05:44,635
There are two related parameters that are called top-K,

84

00:05:44,635  -->  00:05:49,080
which specifies the number of tokens with the highest probability,

85

00:05:49,080  -->  00:05:54,505
the generation process should consider when selecting the next token.

86

00:05:54,505  -->  00:05:57,990
The other parameter is top-P,

87

00:05:57,990  -->  00:06:03,220
which can specify the total probability of most probable tokens,

88

00:06:03,220  -->  00:06:08,050
a generation process should consider when selecting the next token.

89

00:06:08,050  -->  00:06:11,310
Let's take a look at the top-K parameter.

90

00:06:11,310  -->  00:06:13,580
If we set top-K to three,

91

00:06:13,580  -->  00:06:16,320
it means that when generating text,

92

00:06:16,320  -->  00:06:22,080
we will pick the next token from only top three tokens and model has returned.

93

00:06:22,080  -->  00:06:26,520
In this example, it will randomly select either power, trained,

94

00:06:26,520  -->  00:06:31,540
or vulnerable, but it won't pick A or few or any other tokens.

95

00:06:31,540  -->  00:06:33,160
If we set it to six,

96

00:06:33,160  -->  00:06:36,680
it means that we will pick from top six tokens.

97

00:06:36,680  -->  00:06:42,640
Selecting the higher number of K means that the result text might get more creative,

98

00:06:42,640  -->  00:06:46,200
or it might diverge into somewhat unrelated areas.

99

00:06:46,200  -->  00:06:48,620
But if I set the value too high,

100

00:06:48,620  -->  00:06:50,820
it can start generating nonsense.

101

00:06:50,820  -->  00:06:56,260
The final parameter that we can use to control token generation is called T,

102

00:06:56,260  -->  00:07:03,260
and this parameter affects the probability distribution returned by the softmax layer.

103

00:07:03,260  -->  00:07:06,930
To use it, we divide the logit values by

104

00:07:06,930  -->  00:07:12,290
this T parameter before we use these values in the soft max calculations.

105

00:07:12,290  -->  00:07:18,510
If we set it to one, then the softmax function will just return the regular output.

106

00:07:18,510  -->  00:07:21,990
However, if we make T parameter smaller,

107

00:07:21,990  -->  00:07:27,750
then logits with higher values will get significantly higher probability,

108

00:07:27,750  -->  00:07:31,070
increasing the chance that they will be selected.

109

00:07:31,070  -->  00:07:37,450
It also decreases the chances that tokens with lower logit values will be selected.

110

00:07:37,450  -->  00:07:42,100
On the other hand, if we set temperature to a higher value,

111

00:07:42,100  -->  00:07:45,600
the probability distribution becomes more flat,

112

00:07:45,600  -->  00:07:51,720
increasing the chance that the value with lower logit values will be selected.

113

00:07:51,720  -->  00:07:53,935
Using Hugging Face,

114

00:07:53,935  -->  00:07:58,660
we can provide values for all the parameters we've discussed so far.

115

00:07:58,660  -->  00:08:01,430
When using the generator function,

116

00:08:01,430  -->  00:08:06,480
we can provide do sample to enable multinomial sampling,

117

00:08:06,480  -->  00:08:12,615
specify the number of beams in the beam search and provide top-K,

118

00:08:12,615  -->  00:08:19,240
top-P or temperature to influence the degree of randomness in the output.
